When the electric overload current passes through the circuit breaker, the bimetal responds by deflecting, until touching the switching mechanism. After that, the bimetal responds to the overload current by applying a bending force on the arm of the switching mechanism. The switching mechanism has mechanical resistance, where the switching mechanism breaks only if the required force is applied. Hence, the temperature of the bimetal must reach the tripping threshold to deflect and apply the tripping force. The bending force applied by the cantilever bimetal when it is fixed from one side and restrained from another side when its temperature rises from T1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
